INFORMING PUBLIC POLICY DEBATES

Much of the fellowship involved engagement with Scottish Government officials, local authority officials and others on the implications of the debates taking place. This included invited to private meetings with senior figures including the Permanent Secretary in the Scottish Government and a number of local authority chief executives. Presentations were given on the future of local governance and public services in the context of these debates. These presentations were mainly made at public events but mostly involved key decision-makers in different parts of Scotland ranging from the Shetland, Orkney, Borders and different parts of the Scottish central belt. Subsequently I have been involved in helping shape policy developments in discussions with SOLACE.

A report written during this period on the Future of Local Governance was submitted by the Society of Local Authority Chief Executives (SOLACE) to both the Commission on Local Democracy (the report of the Commission suggests heavy use was made of the information contained in the submission) and the Smith Commission. That report and subsequent work with SOLACE is informing public policy debates.

Since the end of the fellowship and consequent on the fellowship, SOLACE asked me to write related report on 'Educational Governance' post Smith. This has recently been submitted and I addressed SOLACE (Scotland) Development away day 2015 in Kirkwall, Orkney on Friday 20th August 2015 on this subject. This report is to be the basis of SOLACE Scotland's work on educational governance over the next year.

This report was also referred to in evidence to the Scottish parliament Local Govt and Regeneration Committee submitted by the Society of Local Authority Lawyers and Administrators:
http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/S4_LocalGovernmentandRegenerationCommittee/lg_SOLAR.pdf

and I was quoted by the Local Government and Regeneration Committee in its 8th report (session 2014) on Flexibility and Autonomy in Local Government):
http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/S4_LocalGovernmentandRegenerationCommittee/Reports/lgR-14-08w.pdf
