I was quoted in the report of the Commons Public Administration Select Committee report on civil service neutrality:
http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmpubadm/111/11105.htm
at paras. 17, 23, 48.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2013</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>03687602-75B3-4469-A7BC-CA66EAE6A0A2</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>546cffd77c2308.13991221</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The recent Scottish independence referendum involved debates with deep roots in Scottish politics involving four inter-related sets of issues: Scotland's constitutional status and relations with the rest of the UK (rUK) (and beyond); party politics and the Scottish party system; the politics of national identity; and public policy concerns (especially the extent to which Scotland is able to diverge in policy choices from rUK). The central contention of the outputs is that the referendum was about far more than identity or Scotland's constitutional status and that each of these four elements outlined above were inter-related and contributed to what we refer to as 'The Scottish Question'. This became evident in the expansive debates across Scotland during the referendum, though less evident in media presentations of the referendum. According to a range of commentators, these expansive debates engaged the public in an unprecedented manner. In essence, the sharp distinction between constitutional politics and normal politics, outlined by Bruce Ackerman in various works discussing 'constitutional moments', broke down in the context of the Scottish referendum. While it might be contended that the referendum was evidence of 'constitutional politics' as the 'highest form of politics' (Ackerman 1984:1022), this occurred because 'normal' (i.e. non-constitutional politics) were integral to the referendum debates.
Another feature of the work focused on the manner of engagement of different interests in these debates. It was suggested that the sharp distinction between governing and campaigning mindsets (as outlined in Gutmann and Thompson's 'The Spirit of Compromise') has some value in understanding the politics of the referendum but breaks down in some instances evident in the manner in which the referendum created space in which many matters, including public service reform, and the future of local democracy occurred. In essence, the referendum allowed from more debate rather than inhibited or limited it. however, there were issues at the core of the debate - including EU membership and the currency - that were matters of high contention and in which debate followed the campaign - uncompromising, little respect for opponents - hallmarks of this style of politics.
A crucial aspect of the manner in which everyday governing concerns insinuated themselves into the referendum debates (especially amongst elites) was evident in debates on local governance. The referendum witnessed considerable debate, especially in Scotland's northern and western islands, on the future of local governance.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The findings might be further tested in any future referendum e.g. on EU membership. To what extent will actors use the EU referendum as a platform for raising other matters, forcing each side to engage on matters not necessarily or obviously directly related to EU membership.

